In the treatment of Russian authors one will often (or maybe not so often) come across the russian word ''kalembur''. It means pun - and especially [[Nikolai Gogol]] is known for his extensive use of kalemburs in his texts. In 1919 the russian [[formalist]] Boris Ejchenbaum wrote a anticle about Gogol's short story [[The_Overcoat|"The Overcoat"]] in which he treats Gogols use of ''kalemburs''. The article has become a classic in [[formalism (literature)|literary formalism]].

See also: [[Russian formalism]].

